text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!geographical locations of english regional dialects (ft. the Cot-Caught merger)%0a%0a:Author: taylor000%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe Cot-Caught merger and locating English regional dialects%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aPeople in different areas speak differently. This is called a regional dialect and we’ve already discussed it in class. However, one interesting application of this is that it’s possible to triangulate someone’s location (or rather, where they grew up / other sociocultural influences) based entirely on their speech? %0a%0aThere’s a fun NYT quiz demonstrating this (we all get a free subscription through CMU) - www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/upshot/dialect-quiz-map.html - and I’m here to talk a bit more about the way it works and how it can be applied in a more academic context.%0a%0aRemember the cot-caught merger? It’s a vowel merger (formerly called the “low back merger”) in which speakers in some English dialects do not differentiate between the vowels in minimal pairs like cot/caught, bot/bought, and pond/pawned. The IPA symbols for these low back vowels are /ɑ/ and /ɔ/ (we use /ʌ/ in this class), but more interestingly, this merger is not uniformly distributed across North America. Regions like the “South”, the “Inland North”, and the “Northeast Corridor” (we’re not going to get into the specifics of where exactly these are, but you probably have good enough ideas in your head) seem to resist this merger most strongly. Thus, if you exhibit this merger, it’s likely that you’re from one of these regions (or linguistically influenced in some way by people/media from there).%0a%0aBut how can we figure out someone’s location with this information? There are many other vowel mergers and various pieces of phonetic / lexical information like the Don-Dawn merger, the Southern Vowel Shift, Pin-Pen merger, Dew-Do merger (these are ones related to the “south” in specific, more can be found at en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phonological_history_of_English).%0a%0a%0aTLDR: language changes SO often and that’s SO COOL %0a%0aResources used:%0awww.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/upshot/dialect-quiz-map.html%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phonological_history_of_English%0ahttps://www.ling.upenn.edu/phono_atlas/home.html%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cot%25E2%2580%2593caught_merger%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sound_change%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: E:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)%0a(:Title: geographical locations of english regional dialects (ft. the Cot-Caught merger):)
